One numerical explanatory variable

Simple linear regression

\[\hat{y} = b_0 + b_1 \cdot x\]

library(broom)
score_model <- lm(score ~ bty_avg, data = evals_ch5)
tidy(score_model)

\[\widehat{score} = b_0 + b_{bty\_avg} \cdot \textrm{bty_avg}\] \[ = 3.88 + 0.067 \cdot \textrm{bty_avg}\]

age_model <- lm(score ~ age, data = evals_ch5)
tidy(age_model)

\[ = 4.46 - 0.006 \cdot \textrm{age}\] #### Residuals

Creating a regression model

Because the explanatory variable here (continent) is categorical, it cant go directly into the model. Rather, the baseline becomes the intercept, and the estimates for the remaining data are offsets relative to the baseline.

lifeExp_model <- lm(lifeExp ~ continent, data = gapminder2007)
tidy(lifeExp_model)

Wriring the equation for regression with a single categorical explanatory variable requires introducing the concept of an indicator function. An indicator function, \(1_A(x)\) is one that takes the value \(1\) if \(x\) is in \(A\) and \(0\) otherwise. So \(1_{\textrm{Amer}}(x)\) would be \(1\) if \(x\) were in the Americas and \(0\) otherwise. Its basically a dummy variable.

With that in mind, the equation for the regression line here is just:

\[ \hat{y} = \widehat{\textrm{life exp}} = b_0 + b_{\textrm{Amer}}(x) \cdot 1_{\textrm{Amer}}(x) + b_{\textrm{Euro}}(x) \cdot 1_{\textrm{Euro}}(x) + \\ b_{\textrm{Asia}}(x) \cdot 1_{\textrm{Asia}}(x) + b_{\textrm{Ocean}}(x) \cdot 1_{\textrm{Ocean}}(x) \]

(lifeExp_regression_table <- augment_columns(lifeExp_model, gapminder2007) %>% 
  select(country, continent, lifeExp, .fitted, .resid))
lifeExp_regression_table %>% 
  arrange(.resid) %>% 
  head(5)
lifeExp_regression_table %>% 
  arrange(desc(.resid)) %>% 
  head(5)

gdpPercap_model <- lm(gdpPercap ~ continent, data = gapminder2007)
